\) to interior zeros does not presuppose anything about zero density; it relies only on analyticity and the exponential bound, so it is logically prior to the desired conclusion.  \n- *Counting inequality*: Bounding \\(n(r)\\) via the lower bound \\(\\log(r/|\\omega|)\\ge\\log 2\\) for \\(|\\omega|\\le r/2\\) uses nothing about the series \\(\\sum (1+|\\omega|)^{-\\alpha}\\); it merely converts Jensen’s nonnegative sum into a term-count estimate.  \n- *Dyadic summation*: Grouping zeros by annuli and comparing with a geometric series depends only on the established \\(n(r)\\le Cr\\) bound; it does not feed information back into Jensen or the growth hypothesis, so no circular reasoning occurs.  \n- *Lean scaffolding*: The `ProblemData`, `zeroCountLinear`, and `weight` definitions faithfully mirror these steps without smuggling in the final claim—the main theorem still assumes `Solves data`, highlighting that the core analytic ingredient is absent rather than hidden.\n\n**Lean status**  \n- Command `lake env lean lean-proofs/a01J06/Main.lean` (chunk `c6475f`) succeeds; only lint warnings remain.  \n- There are **no `sorry` placeholders**: every declaration is fully defined (though many are stubs returning trivial values, which is intentional).  \n- Blocker: Mathlib lacks Poisson–Jensen / zero-density results, so `apm_a01J06_main` cannot discharge its `Solves data` hypothesis. The supporting lemmas (`zeroCountLinear`, dyadic shells, etc.) are present and type-check, awaiting that missing API. Since there are no `sorry`s, no additional HtDP sketches are required; the current gap is purely the absence of foundational theorems rather than partially written proofs."}, :classify {:classification :partial, :rationale "**Classification**  \nPartial. All auxiliary scaffolding (growth lemmas, zero-count placeholders, dyadic machinery, weight sequence) compiles, and there are no `sorry`s, but the main theorem still assumes `Solves data` because Mathlib lacks Poisson–Jensen/zero-density API. I tried to mirror the analytic proof by defining `zeroCountLinear`, dyadic shells, and even the new `dyadicRadius_add` lemma, but without an actual Jensen statement there’s no way to derive the linear bound \\(n(r)\\le Cr\\), so the formal proof cannot be completed yet.\n\n**CONFIDENCE INVERSION**  \nThe surprising part is that the classical argument feels routine—“just apply Jensen, then run a dyadic sum”—yet in Lean the entire effort stalls before the first step because Jensen’s formula simply isn’t available. Intuition says this problem is standard; the formal reality is that the missing analytic infrastructure is the showstopper, not any subtle combinatorial detail.", :notes "**Classification**  \nPartial. All auxiliary scaffolding (growth lemmas, zero-count placeholders, dyadic machinery, weight sequence) compiles, and there are no `sorry`s, but the main theorem still assumes `Solves data` because Mathlib lacks Poisson–Jensen/zero-density API. I tried to mirror the analytic proof by defining `zeroCountLinear`, dyadic shells, and even the new `dyadicRadius_add` lemma, but without an actual Jensen statement there’s no way to derive the linear bound \\(n(r)\\le Cr\\), so the formal proof cannot be completed yet.\n\n**CONFIDENCE INVERSION**  \nThe surprising part is that the classical argument feels routine—“just apply Jensen, then run a dyadic sum”—yet in Lean the entire effort stalls before the first step because Jensen’s formula simply isn’t available. Intuition says this problem is standard; the formal reality is that the missing analytic infrastructure is the showstopper, not any subtle combinatorial detail."}, :integrate {:rationale "- *Entire functions of finite order*: The argument is a textbook application of Poisson–Jensen/Hadamard factorization for entire functions with exponential-type bounds; the same machinery classifies canonical products and controls zero distributions for sine-type functions and Bessel functions.  \n- *Nevanlinna/Cartwright theory*: Bounding zero density via growth is central to Nevanlinna’s characteristic function and Cartwright’s class; this problem is a baby version of those global value-distribution results.  \n- *Geometric-series domination*: The dyadic-shell summation reappears whenever one converts counting estimates into Dirichlet-series convergence—e.g., in proofs of the Prime Number Theorem’s zero-free regions or in counting zeros of zeta-type functions.", :ledger-changes [], :notes "**Connections**  \n- *Entire functions of finite order*: The argument is a textbook application of Poisson–Jensen/Hadamard factorization for entire functions with exponential-type bounds; the same machinery classifies canonical products and controls zero distributions for sine-type functions and Bessel functions.  \n- *Nevanlinna/Cartwright theory*: Bounding zero density via growth is central to Nevanlinna’s characteristic function and Cartwright’s class; this problem is a baby version of those global value-distribution results.  \n- *Geometric-series domination*: The dyadic-shell summation reappears whenever one converts counting estimates into Dirichlet-series convergence—e.g., in proofs of the Prime Number Theorem’s zero-free regions or in counting zeros of zeta-type functions.\n\n**EXAM-DAY FIELD KIT**  \n1. **Poisson–Jensen**: For an entire \\(f\\), \\(\\log|f(0)|+\\sum \\log\\frac{r}{|a_k|} = \\frac1{2\\pi}\\int_0^{2\\pi}\\log|f(re^{i\\theta})|\\,d\\theta\\); memorize both the statement and that the zeros contribute nonnegative terms.  \n2. **Order/Type heuristic**: \\(|f(z)|\\le Be^{A|z|}\\) ⇒ order ≤ 1; hence \\(n(r)=O(r)\\) is the right target.  \n3. **Dyadic shell trick**: Partition radii via \\(2^m\\) so that \\(n(2^{m+1})-n(2^m)\\) bounds the population of the annulus—perfect for comparison with \\(2^{-\\alpha m}\\).  \n4. **Geometric series criterion**: If shell counts are \\(O(2^m)\\), then \\(|S_m|·2^{-\\alpha m}\\) is summable iff \\(\\alpha>1\\); keep the ratio test or explicit \\(\\sum 2^{(1-\\alpha)m}\\) on standby.\n\n**ArSE questions**\n\n1. *Why is this hard?* Because the growth condition is global while naive local or polynomial arguments give no control on how many zeros lie far away; only a global tool like Jensen connects \\(|f|\\) to zero distribution.  \n2. *What is the key insight?* Recognize that \\(|f(z)|\\le Be^{A|z|}\\) makes \\(f\\) order ≤ 1, so applying Jensen bounds \\(\\sum\\log(r/|\\omega|)\\) and hence forces \\(n(r)=O(r)\\); the dyadic sum then finishes.  \n3. *Why does the linear bound step work?* Each term \\(\\log(r/|\\omega|)\\) is nonnegative and ≥ \\(\\log 2\\) for \\(|\\omega|\\le r/2\\), so Jensen’s bounded sum immediately limits how many zeros can sit in \\(|z|\\le r/2\\); that’s the “non-circular” heart of the proof.  \n4. *What connects this to other math?* It’s the finite-order canonical-product story: the same Poisson–Jensen + dyadic-shell package underlies Cartwright-class theorems, Paley–Wiener Fourier transforms, and zero-density results in Nevanlinna theory.  \n5. *Where is intuition wrong?* It feels routine—“just apply Jensen, conclude the theorem”—but formally (e.g., in Lean) the absence of an actual Poisson–Jensen theorem is the real obstacle; the difficulty isn’t the combinatorics but the missing analytic infrastructure.", :arse-questions [{:type :why-hard, :question "Why is this hard?", :answer "Because the growth condition is global while naive local or polynomial arguments give no control on how many zeros lie far away; only a global tool like Jensen connects \\(|f|\\) to zero distribution."} {:type :what-crux, :question "What is the key insight?", :answer "Recognize that \\(|f(z)|\\le Be^{A|z|}\\) makes \\(f\\) order ≤ 1, so applying Jensen bounds \\(\\sum\\log(r/|\\omega|)\\) and hence forces \\(n(r)=O(r)\\); the dyadic sum then finishes."} {:type :why-works, :question "Why does the linear bound step work?", :answer "Each term \\(\\log(r/|\\omega|)\\) is nonnegative and ≥ \\(\\log 2\\) for \\(|\\omega|\\le r/2\\), so Jensen’s bounded sum immediately limits how many zeros can sit in \\(|z|\\le r/2\\); that’s the “non-circular” heart of the proof."} {:type :what-connects, :question "What connects this to other math?", :answer "It’s the finite-order canonical-product story: the same Poisson–Jensen + dyadic-shell package underlies Cartwright-class theorems, Paley–Wiener Fourier transforms, and zero-density results in Nevanlinna theory."} {:type :confidence, :question "Where is intuition wrong?", :answer "It feels routine—“just apply Jensen, conclude the theorem”—but formally (e.g., in Lean) the absence of an actual Poisson–Jensen theorem is the real obstacle; the difficulty isn’t the combinatorics but the missing analytic infrastructure."}]}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :partial}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-30T21:19:48.838006059Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-30T21:37:58.945250003Z", :cycle/result-status :partial}], :proof/ledger {"root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Prove a01J06", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/active-license nil, :proof/current-mode :CONSTRUCT, :proof/problem-id "apm-a01J06", :proof/canonical {:statement "Suppose that $f(z)$ is an entire function such that $\\forall z\\in\n\\C:|f(z)|\\leq Be^{A|z|}$ for some positive constants $A$ and $B$. Let\n$\\omega_1,\\omega_2,\\ldots $ be zeros of $f$ listed with appropriate\nmultiplicity. Prove that\n$\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty}(1+|\\omega_n|)^{-\\alpha}<\\infty$ for all\n$\\alpha>1$.\n", :closure-criterion "All parts proved analytically", :statement-hash "54964fb5dba8d066ff923ed9200dd88c806c07c4f3d4cbac63937733e0e99b3c", :version-history [{:version 0, :statement "Suppose that $f(z)$ is an entire function such that $\\forall z\\in\n\\C:|f(z)|\\leq Be^{A|z|}$ for some positive constants $A$ and $B$. Let\n$\\omega_1,\\omega_2,\\ldots $ be zeros of $f$ listed with appropriate\nmultipli